{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ce53c26d-cef5-43f5-9751-c23228c41496","content":"## What Changed\n\nC# 14 adds **implicit span conversions** — `T[]` now implicitly converts to `ReadOnlySpan<T>`. This changes overload resolution:\n\n| .NET 9 | .NET 10 |\n|---|---|\n| `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)` | `MemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` ✅ preferred |\n\nThe `MemoryExtensions` overload wins because `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is more specific than `IEnumerable<T>`. But `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a **ref struct** — it cannot be represented in expression trees. The interpreter blows up at runtime when it hits this method call.\n\n## Fix\n\nDisambiguate so the compiler picks the LINQ overload:\n\n```csharp\n// Option 1: cast away the span conversion\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);\n\n// Option 2: call Enumerable.Contains explicitly (no extension-method syntax)\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);\n```\n\nEither form forces resolution back to `Enumerable.Contains`, which the expression-tree interpreter handles fine.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"249ad251-5b9f-47a7-939d-ca9823a2f45b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a breaking change in .NET 10 / C# 14 that affects LINQ expression trees calling `.Contains()` on arrays. Let me think about what changed.\n\nIn C# 14 / .NET 10, there's a significant change related to extension members. Specifically, the `System.Linq.Enumerable.Contains<T>()` method resolution changed because arrays now have different method resolution behavior.\n\nActually, let me think more carefully. The issue is likely related to the fact that in .NET 10, `int[]` now implements `IEnumerable<int>` differently, or more likely, it's about the extension method resolution change.\n \nThe real breaking change is probably that in .NET 10, `Contains` resolution on arrays s