ontains` isn't translatable to LINQ expressions. is more specific than `IEnumerable<T>`\n4. The expression tree captures this as a call to `MemoryExtensions.Contains`\n5. At runtime, the expression tree interpreter can't handle `ReadOnlySpan<T>` (a ref struct) and throws\n\nWait, but can you even create an expression tree that references `ReadOnlySpan<T>`? The compiler should reject this at compile time because expression trees can't contain ref struct types.\n\nHmm, let me reconsider. Maybe the compiler does produce an error at compile time but the user described it as \"runtime\"? Or maybe the compiler doesn't catch it and it fails at runtime?\n\nActually, in C# 14, there was explicitly discussion about expression trees and how they handle the new span conversions. The compiler might need special handling here.\n\nLet me think about this from a different angle. What if the issue is that in .NET 10, the compiler still selects `Enumerable.Contains` when building expression tree lambdas due to restrictions on ref struct types in expression trees, but then something about how that method works internally has changed or how the expression tree interpreter handles it has shifted. I should look at the actual .NET 10 breaking changes to see what's documented here rather than speculating further. The user mentioned this throws at runtime, which is key—the expression tree might compile successfully even though `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a ref struct, but then fail when the runtime tries to execute it. Alternatively, the compiler could be throwing an error and the user is conflating compile-time and runtime errors. Either way, the root cause is that C# 14's implicit span conversions are changing which overload gets selected, pulling in `MemoryExtensions.Contains` instead of `Enumerable.Contains`, and ref structs can't be used in expression trees.\n\nThe solution is to explicitly cast the array to `IEnumerable<int>` to force the LINQ overload, or call `Enumerable.Contains` directly